Answer: The problem in your code is that the Scanner class in Java uses whitespace as the default delimiter, and it stops reading when it encounters the first whitespace it encounters. This is why only the first line is being read in part one of your code.

To fix this, you can use the Scanner method `useDelimiter` to change the delimiter to a newline character (`\n`). This tells the Scanner to stop reading when it encounters a newline character, which is what you want in both parts of your code.

Here's the corrected code:

```java
import java.io.ByteArrayInputStream;
import java.io.FileOutputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStream;
import java.io.OutputStream;
import java.io.OutputStreamWriter;
import java.io.PrintWriter;
import java.util.NoSuchElementException;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class BadParse {
    public static String getNextEntry(InputStream in) {
        Scanner sin = new Scanner(in);
        sin.useDelimiter("\n"); // Change delimiter to newline
        try {
            String ssn = sin.next();
            String name = sin.next();
            int age = sin.nextInt();
            return name + "(" + ssn + ") is " + age + " years old.";
        } catch (NoSuchElementException e) {
            return null;
        }
    }

    public static void putNextEntry(String ssn, String name, int age, OutputStream out) {
        PrintWriter pout = new PrintWriter(new OutputStreamWriter(out));
        pout.print(ssn + " ");
        pout.print(name + " ");
        pout.print(age + " ");
        pout.flush();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        // Part I
        String input = "1234567890 John 20\n0987654321 Beth 18\n2468101214 Jack 19\n";
        InputStream in = new ByteArrayInputStream(input.getBytes());
        String entry;
        while ((entry = getNextEntry(in)) != null) {
            System.out.println(entry);
        }

        // Part II
        OutputStream out = new FileOutputStream("data");
        putNextEntry("1234567890", "John", 20, out);
        putNextEntry("0987654321", "Beth", 18, out);
        putNextEntry("2468101214", "Jack", 19, out);
        out.close();
    }
}
```

This code should now correctly read and print all the entries in both parts of your code.

Note: The `useDelimiter("\n")` method sets the delimiter to a newline character, which tells the Scanner to stop reading when it encounters a newline. The `next()` method reads the next token from the input as a String, and the `nextInt()` method reads the next token from the input as an int.

Also, remember to call `flush()` on the PrintWriter to ensure that all output is written immediately.

Finally, don't forget to close the OutputStream after you're done writing to it to free up system resources.

I hope this helps clarify the issue and provides a solution to your problem.

